    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(11) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "And this is the law of the sacrifice of peace offerings.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—That is, the rites to be observed in connection with this sacrifice. As in the case of the sin offering (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 4:24-31",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " with ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 6:24-30",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") and the trespass offering (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 5:1-13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " with ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 7:1-10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), so here (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 7:11-21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), we have more specific and fuller directions given to the priests with regard to the peace offerings, about which orders had previously been given to the people (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 3:1-15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ").",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Which he shall offer.—That is, he who feels it his duty to offer it to the Lord. This common Hebrew idiom of using a verb with he in it without an antecedent is better expressed in English by the impersonal, which one shall offer, or by the passive, which shall be offered. (See Leviticus 7:20-29.) Three classes of peace offerings are specified—(1) an acknowledgment of mercies received, (2) as a vow offering, (3) as a freewill offering.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "Which he shall offer.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—That is, he who feels it his duty to offer it to the Lord. This common Hebrew idiom of using a verb with ",
            "children": []
