  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Benson Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Leviticus 7:11",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Leviticus 7:11",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "This is the law of the sacrifice of peace-offerings — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "These are the only sort of offerings to be spoken of. There were several sorts of them, which required various rites. The first was a ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "gratulatory ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "offering, or a sacrifice of thanksgiving, so called because it was offered to God for some particular benefit received, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 7:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Such sacrifices were accompanied with feasting, and sometimes with high demonstrations of joy, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Samuel 11:15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 8:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Of these the psalmist speaks, when he says, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Let them sacrifice the sacrifices of thanksgiving, and declare his works with rejoicing, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "<19A722>",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 107:22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The second was a ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "votive-offering, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "or ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "vow, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "being also a sacrifice of thanksgiving, but offered in consequence of a vow, or religious oath, whereby the party obliged himself to offer to God such a sacrifice, in case of receiving some particular benefit. The third was a ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "voluntary offering, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "being a sacrifice freely made beforehand, in the nature of a prayer for obtaining some future blessing, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 7:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; or, as Le Clerc explains it, a voluntary offering was a sacrifice offered, not for any particular benefit either received or expected, but merely from the overflowing of a heart grateful to God for his goodness in general. We find this oblation plainly distinguished from a votive-offering, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 22:23",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
