  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verses 11-21.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - Further ritual of the peace offering (see note on chapter Leviticus 3:1). There are three sorts of peace offerings - thank offerings (verses 12-15), votive offerings, and voluntary offerings (verses 16-18). Of these, the thank offerings were made in thankful memorial for past mercies; votive offerings were made in fulfillment of a vow previously taken, that such offering should be presented if a terrain condition were fulfilled. Voluntary offerings differ from votive offerings by not having been previously vowed, and from thank offerings by not having reference to any special mercy received. The thank offering must be eaten by the offerer and his friends, on the same day that it was offered; the votive and the voluntary offerings, which were inferior to the thank offering in sanctity, on the same day or the next. The reason why a longer time was not given probably was that the more the meal was delayed, the less would a religious character be attached to it. The necessity of a quick consumption also took away the temptation of acting grudgingly towards those with whom the feast might be shared, and it likewise precluded the danger of the flesh becoming corrupted. If any of the flesh remained till the third day, it was to be ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "burnt with fire",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; if eaten on that day, it should not be ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "accepted or imputed unto him that offered",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", that is, it should not be regarded as a sacrifice of sweet savour to God, but an abomination (literally, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "a stench",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and whoever ate it should ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "bear his iniquity",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", that is, should be guilty of an offense, requiring, probably, a sin offering to atone for it. The bread gift accompanying the animal sacrifice was to consist of three kinds of unleavened cakes, and one cake of leavened bread, and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "one out of the whole oblation",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", that is, one cake of each kind, was to be offered by heaving and then given to the officiating priest, the remaining cakes forming a part of the offerer's festive meal. If any one took part of a feast on a peace offering while in a state of Levitical uncleanness, he was to be ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "cut off from his people",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", that is, excommunicated, without permission to recover immediate communion by offering a sin offering. St. Paul joined in a votive offering (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 21:26",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Leviticus 7:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The Law of the Peace-Offerings, \"which he shall offer to Jehovah\" (the subject is to be supplied from the verb), contains instructions, (1) as to the bloodless accompaniment to these sacrifices (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 7:12-14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), (2) as to the eating of the flesh of the sacrifices (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 7:15-21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), with the prohibition against eating fat and blood (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 7:22-27",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and (3) as to Jehovah's share of these sacrifices (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 7:28-36",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). - In ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 7:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 7:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " three classes of shelamim are mentioned, which differ according to their occasion and design, viz., whether they were brought על־תּודה, upon the ground of praise, i.e., to praise God for blessings received or desired, or as vow-offerings, or thirdly, as freewill-offerings (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 7:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). To (lit., upon, in addition to) the sacrifice of thanksgiving (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 7:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", \"sacrifice of thanksgiving of his peace-offerings,\" ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 7:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 7:15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") they were to present \"unleavened cakes kneaded with oil, and flat cakes anointed with oil (see at ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 2:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and roasted fine flour (see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 6:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") mixed as cakes with oil,\" i.e., cakes made of fine flour roasted with oil, and thoroughly kneaded with oil (on the construction, see Ges. 139, 2; Ewald 284 a). This last kind of cakes kneaded with oil is also called oil-bread-cake (\"a cake of oiled bread,\" ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 8:26",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 29:23",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), or \"cake unleavened, kneaded with oil\" (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 29:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and probably differed from the former simply in the fact that it was more thoroughly saturated with oil, inasmuch as it was not only made of flour that had been mixed with oil in the kneading, but the flour itself was first of all roasted in oil, and then the dough was moistened still further with oil in the process of kneading. ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]